  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT305-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">kāppumikutikkaṇ tōḻi aṟattoṭu niṟpāḷākat taṉatu āṟṟāmai tōṉṟat talaimakaḷ
          taṉṉuḷḷē kūṟiyatu </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered in herself by HER, so that her lack of strength
          appeared, while the confidante stood firm in duty, during an increase in guarding. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT305">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> kaṇṭara vanta kāma voḷḷeri</l>
          <l> yeṉpuṟa naliyiṉu mavaroṭu pēṇic</l>
          <l> ceṉṟunā muyaṅkaṟ karuṅkāṭ ciyamē</l>
          <l> vantañar kaḷaitalai yavarāṟ ṟalarē</l>
          <l> yuyttaṉar viṭāar pirittiṭai kaḷaiyār</l>
          <l> kuppaik kōḻit taṉippōr pōla</l>
          <l> viḷivāṅku viḷiyi ṉallatu</l>
          <l> kaḷaivō rilaiyā ṉuṟṟa nōyē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l rend="indent">Even though the bright flame of desire,</l>
          <l rend="indent7">that came as the eye brought [it] on,</l>
          <l rend="indent">afflicts [us] to the bone, having developed esteem towards him,<note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> varoṭu pēṇi | ceṉṟu </term>? How to understand this phrase? Does it refer to an act of elopement? Or can <term xml:lang="ta"> cel-tal </term> here be used as an auxiliary, and then coordinate to <term xml:lang="ta"> muyaṅkaṟku </term>, as above? In this case the instrumental on <term xml:lang="ta"> avaroṭu </term> remains strange; one would expect an accusative. </note> </l>
          <l>we [are] a rare sight [difficult] to embrace.<note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> kāṭciyam </term>, pronominal noun in denominative function to <term xml:lang="ta"> kāṭci </term>, strangely interfers with the usual semantics of verbal noun plus <term xml:lang="ta"> aru </term>, "difficult to do x". Does the line mingle two phrases: "we are a rare sight and thus difficult to embrace"? T.V.G.'s interpretation, that she is one to have the opportunity is not backed up by the lexica, though syntax here seems to speak in favour of it, because the nominative <term xml:lang="ta"> nām </term> preceding the <term xml:lang="ta"> uyaṅkaṟku </term> should mean that SHE is the subject ("we are rarely to be seen in embracing").   </note> </l>
          <l>He is not able to come [and] remove [my] sorrow.</l>
          <l>No one is there to remove the pain I have,</l>
          <l>if not it perishes <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta">	viḷiyiṉ allatu </term>: how to understand this construction (cf. <term xml:lang="ta"> cāyiṉ allatu </term> in KT 152.3)? Is this simply the way to negate a conditional? </note> [then and] there, <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> viḷivu āṅku viḷivatu </term> looks slightly strange, but might thus be understood as an intensifying figura etymologica.</note> </l>
          <l rend="indent2">like cocks in a lone battle over a heap:</l>
          <l rend="indent4">he who has sent [them and] does not leave [them] off,</l>
          <l rend="indent4">doesn't separate [and] in between remove [them]. <note place="foot"> This line probably has to be read as a part of the cock fighting simile, but how to understand its construction? The point seems to be that there is nobody to separate the fighting cocks, just as there is nobody to alleviate HER pain.    </note></l>

        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
